<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>26 Allingham St</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by Frances Christian Balfour [FBB0081]</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Enquiry:  Future of the BBC</span></p><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:20.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">I write as a member of the public and a citizen who greatly enjoys watching many BBC </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">programmes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.  I consider that the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">licence</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> fee is incredibly good value for money.  I responded to a DCMS questionnaire at the time of the last Charter Review and was invited to attend, and attended, the seminars on all the relevant issues at the DCMS.   I support the current submission of the Campaign for Press and Broadcasting Freedom (CPBF), with its precise comments and proposals prepared by academics who are experts on media issues.  These are my more personal views in support of the BBC. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:20.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">What should the BBC be for and what is the purpose of public broadcasting?</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:20.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Public broadcasting should provide a top quality service that informs, educates and entertains everyone in the country, poor as well as rich.  It should be able to do this free from commercial pressures and government control.  Lord Reith set up the BBC as a public corporation to be governed in the public interest at </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">arms</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> length from government and free from commercial pressure so that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">It</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> could fulfill this objective.  Its unique structure has provided a model for public broadcasting and has meant British public broadcasting is high quality, wide-ranging in scope and exemplary. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:20.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">How well has the BBC performed in the current Charter period in achieving its mission and pubic purposes? </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Sustaining citizenship and civil society; promoting education and learning; stimulating creativity and cultural excellence; representing the UK, its nations, regions and communities; bringing the UK to the world and the world to the UK; and promoting its other purposes, and, in addition, taking a leading role in the switchover to digital television</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:20.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Personally, I think that the BBC has achieved its several public purposes amazingly well, and that in spite of having to deal with a freeze in the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">licence</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> fee in a time of fairly high inflation.  It is, however, noticeable that the freeze in the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">licence</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> fee has led to more repeats.    </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:20.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The recent major scandals concerning Jimmy </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Saville</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and excessive severance pay, shocking though they are, particularly the former, should not make us lose perspective on the vast amount and varied types of wonderful </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">programmes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, produced by hardworking and dedicated staff, that the BBC has broadcast over the years and continues to broadcast. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:20.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The BBC’s News and current affairs </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">programmes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> are an essential part of our national life (though Channel 4 news does provide strong competition to the BBC as a daily news </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">programme</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">).  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Programmes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> like “Watchdog”, and “</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Crimewatch</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">” support maintaining a decent society.  Factual </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">programmes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> inform us of how many individuals contribute to the structure of society.  Last night I watched “Keeping Britain Safe” which dealt with:  how Network Rail deals with ‘leaves on the line’ in autumn, and why they are such a problem; how the fire service copes with bonfire night; how the Royal National Lifeboat Institution has taken on the task of flood </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rescue; how the 999 system was originated; how helicopter air ambulances save lives; and how midwives work in a busy maternity unit.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:20.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The dramatizations of English literature classics such as “Little </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Dorrit</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">”, the broadcasting of Shakespeare’s history plays, the many fascinating and accessible science </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">programmes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, including those of Professor Brian Cox, who opened one </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">programme</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> with a meeting with the current Dr Who, “Simon </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Schama’s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> “History of Britain”, and all the natural history </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">programmes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> from “</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Springwatch</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">” and “</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Autumnwatch</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">” to “Planet Earth and “Africa” inform and educate.  That is not to mention all the educational materials on the website for pupils, including GCSE revision, teachers, and adults.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:20.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Top quality performances of music, opera, ballet and drama which are accessible to the whole nation must encourage creativity.  And “Blue Peter”, now on CBBC, has a proven record of inspiring children over the decades.  Young actors find opportunities on the BBC, and the Young Musician of the Year awards and Radio 6 Music provides a platform for new talent.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.68pt; padding-left:14.32pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Programmes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> such as “</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Countryfile</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">” cover the regions even-handedly, and “Coast” all the regions near the sea.  I always enjoy ‘the news where you are’ and any </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">programmes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> set in the part of the country I come from.  I find myself informed about Northern Ireland, Scotland and Wales, though maybe the residents of those nations may not feel that their national assemblies and concerns are sufficiently represented.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.68pt; padding-left:14.32pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">International news, much enhanced by input from the World Service correspondents, informs us about the world.  “From our Own Correspondent” brings other countries to life.  The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">programmes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Britain exports abroad (at the moment “Dr Who” seems to have gone global) and the World Service broadcasts in national languages take Britain to the world - a form of soft power when we are clearly losing both military and financial power. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.68pt; padding-left:14.32pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The BBC is making </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">emerging communications technologies and services</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">available through its website, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">iPlayer</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and mobile phone access.  Its </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Mediawise</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> website is a valuable guide to using the new technology.  In addition, the huge task of switchover to digital television seems to have taken place without too much stress for the public, presumably thanks to a considerable extent to the BBC’s expertise - though the BBC’s input must have placed an additional burden on its funds.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.68pt; padding-left:14.32pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The BBC’s public purposes are admirable.  The list above does not include on occasion ‘bringing the national together’, or attempting to bridge the gulfs between different communities, though it might be considered that this is included under ‘sustaining citizenship and civil society’. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.68pt; padding-left:14.32pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">What scope scale and remit should the BBC have?</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.68pt; padding-left:14.32pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The BBC should provide a wide range of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">programmes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, news, entertainment including drama and comedy, arts, sport, music, both classical, modern and niche.  It should, as it does, make them accessible on a wide range of platforms, given the rise to prominence of the internet.  Though it is a near impossible task the BBC should aim at reaching all audiences. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.68pt; padding-left:14.32pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Should the BBC’s output and services be provided to any greater or lesser degree for particular audiences?</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.68pt; padding-left:14.32pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">My subjective view is that overall there is a good balance. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">“Match of the Day”, or “Strictly Come Dancing” do not interest me greatly, but millions enjoy them.  BBC3, unsurprisingly, as I am in my 60s, is mainly not my cup of tea, but hopefully it entertains and stimulates the creativity of the - to my generation – incomprehensible young and sometimes it may explain them to me.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.68pt; padding-left:14.32pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">However on the aspect of particular audiences, though I cannot claim to have any systematic knowledge, I intuitively feel that more could be done for the ethnic minorities.  They make up around something like 13 per cent of the population.  They are therefore a minority interest and the great mass of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">licence</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> fee paying viewers may be uninterested in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">programmes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> aimed at these minorities and their many subdivisions. To a certain extent providing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">programmes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> for them is part of Channel 4’s remit.  Yet it is important that they are reached b</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">y</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the BBC.  They too have to pay a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">licence</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> fee.  It is important that they are encouraged to feel that they belong and are valued while their own cultures are respected.  Many of them are young.  In a population that is ageing they are the future.  Is enough thought given to the alienated young, the type of people who rioted in the summer of 2011, talking about ‘the Feds’, not ‘the Met’ or ‘the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">police’.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> They probably see the BBC as part of the hated establishment along with the police.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.68pt; padding-left:14.32pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Maybe the start should be with children, one of the solutions mentioned in the management response to the BBC Trust’s Purpose Remit Survey (</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Cbeebies</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> might lead on to CBBC).  This showed that on the question of ‘The BBC has a wide range of enjoyable and entertaining </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">programmes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and content’ there was a gap between audience’s expectations and perceptions and that the gap was ‘more marked’ among ‘low approvers of the BBC’ - maybe inevitable that there are some - and ethnic minorities.  The survey does perhaps support my intuitive feeling.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.68pt; padding-left:14.32pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">What balance should be struck in what the BBC produces in-house, commissions externally and leaves entirely to others to create?</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.68pt; padding-left:14.32pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">I think that the amount currently produced by Independent producers is more than sufficient or should even be reduced. The BBC has a national responsibility for in-house training on editorial, direction/production and technical fronts.  If too much has to be sourced from outside the BBC it will lose the critical mass to do this.  I understand that in-house training has already been reduced down to a level suitable for producing only 50% since the last Charter agreement and the introduction of the WOCC.  That is a serious loss.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.68pt; padding-left:14.32pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">BBC in-house production has set a standard for external companies to emulate in all areas, though I would particularly like to mention the Natural History Unit in Bristol.  Many of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">programmes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> produced by independent companies are, of course, excellent and fun.  I personally noted “Spooks,” the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">pacy</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> “By Any Means”,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">“The Ambassadors” and “Being Human”. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Some are engaging and informative</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. “Victoria Falls: the Smoke that Thunders”, (which would be one of my 10 desert island TV </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">programmes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">) was produced by Halcyon Media for the Natural History Unit.  “The Life of Muhammad” (a Crescent Films production), shown on BBC 2 in 2011, was produced with a very high standard of research, presentation and, I think, fairness.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.68pt; padding-left:14.32pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">However, I observe that the BBC, when it takes </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">programmes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> from outside, is often drawing on a pool of people that it has itself trained.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Rageh</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Omaar</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, for instance was trained by, and worked as a foreign correspondent for, the BBC.  As such he is a familiar face on our screens, liked and respected by much of the British audience.  As presenter of “The Life of Muhammad” he probably drew many viewers to the subject.  Since this </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">programme</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> throws light on a, to say the least, historically important life in an area where there is a desperate need for bridge building, it is possible the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">programme</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> may have made a contribution to cross-cultural understanding. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.68pt; padding-left:14.32pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Halcyon Media was founded by two people who had both worked for the BBC, Charlie Hamilton James, who </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">stated</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> his career at 16 working with David Attenborough, and Philippa Forrester who also trained and worked at the BBC. Jamie McPherson, who produced “Victoria Falls, the Smoke than Thunders” has been with Halcyon Media ‘since the beginning’ and often works for the BBC on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">programmes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> such a “</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Springwatch</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">” and “Planet Earth”.  Without the training and support from the BBC at the start of their careers, would the founders of Halcyon Media have been able to set up their independent company and achieve what they have?  In these hard times the BBC should take on more trainees in editorial and production in order to create a talent pool for the future, give some young people a start, and save others from job insecurity and intermittent ‘stacking shelves in supermarkets’ type jobs. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.68pt; padding-left:14.32pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Also it is important that the BBC does vet and monitor anything that i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> produced by external producers. Anything that slips through that infringes the BBC’s high standards of accuracy, ethics, and decency that is broadcast under its aegis reflects on the BBC itself.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.68pt; padding-left:14.32pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">How have the BBC’s commercial activities during the current Charter fitted with the BBC’s public purposes and have they achieved an adequate return for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">licence</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> fee payers? What should be the aims, scope and scale of such activities beyond 2016?</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="27" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.68pt; padding-left:14.32pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The BBC’s commercial activities have produced some return for the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">licence</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> fee payer, which is welcome.   But commercial activity should not be allowed to dilute the BBC’s high standards or lead it to produce inferior material and damage its reputation for quality, impartiality and fairness.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="28" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.68pt; padding-left:14.32pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">What role should the BBC play in developing technology and new ways of distributing content?</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="29" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.68pt; padding-left:14.32pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The BBC has always played a leading role in broadcasting technology.  I</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> would be a disgrace if it were to be allowed to lose its predominance and expertise in this field – as a result, for instance, from lack of funding.  Rather it should seek to expand on its traditional technological expertise in order to retain predominance in new technologies and to excel in finding and using new ways of distributing content. There may even be scope for commercial advantage if we have expertise that other countries do not have. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Tony Hall, in his speech to the Voice of the Listener and Viewer Conference on 27 November 2013, outlined plans for using digital technology to make content more accessible on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">iPlayer</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> when and where the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">viewer wishes to watch it.  As the young do nearly everything online it is right that the BBC is addressing this.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="30" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.68pt; padding-left:14.32pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">How should the BBC be funded beyond 2016?</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="31" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.68pt; padding-left:14.32pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">I consider it essential that the BBC should have a secure and regular source of funding, so that it can maintain its high standards of creativity and production, take risks where necessary, and undertake ambitious projects, such as “Planet Earth” and “Africa”, maybe in co-productions, but as a major player. I do not see a better solution than the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">licence</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> fee.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="32" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.68pt; padding-left:14.32pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">(I took part in the consultations for the 2006 Charter renewal and attended the seminars at the DCMS.  In both the general consultation and in the Funding seminar at the DCMS the problems with the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">licence</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> fee were clear.  It is regressive; some people think it is unfair, when all they may want to watch is say, news and one other genre, sport or an arts channel; some commercial companies hate the BBC, as the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">licence</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> fee provides the BBC with a steady income stream, which they consider creates unfair competition which distorts the market.  The conclusion in the “Review of the BBC Royal Charter:  What you said about the BBC”, was that the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">licence</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> fee was the ‘least worst’.  In the seminars, after much deliberation and agonized discussion, the same conclusion eventually prevailed.)  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="33" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.68pt; padding-left:14.32pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">I would also make the point that it seems completely unreasonable that the BBC should have to pay the Sky and Virgin platforms for carrying content it has created, particularly news.  BBC 1 news is apparently the most watched news on Sky (an industry expert, VLV Spring Conference, April 2013).  It is, it seems, often not even </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">recognised</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> that such content is BBC created content.  Any platform which carries BBC created content should pay to do so, as should other distributors such as YouTube, and distributors to mobile phones.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="34" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.68pt; padding-left:14.32pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">And it should be pointed out that all of the BBC’s extensive radio output, including news produced from the same resources as television news, is provided free, as is all the information on the website. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="35" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.68pt; padding-left:14.32pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Is there a case for distributing funding for public service content more widely beyond the BBC?  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="36" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.68pt; padding-left:14.32pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Commercial companies are very able find sources of income and look after themselves.  I do not think they should take funds away from the BBC. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="37" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.68pt; padding-left:14.32pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">What comparisons can be made with the provision of public service content in other countries? </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="38" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.68pt; padding-left:14.32pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In Tony Hall’s speech to The Voice of the Listener and Viewer’s autumn conference </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">on 27 November 2013</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> he quoted a survey of 14 countries who were asked to evaluate their national broadcasting.  In a survey of perception of overall quality UK broadcasting came out top with 72% considering it good or fairly good quality</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,  In</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the survey of channels BBC 1 came out top with 79% considering it good or fairly good quality and BBC 2 was third with 71% (</span><span style="color:#000080; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">www.bbc.co.uk/media centre/speeches/2013/tony-hall-vlv.html</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">).  Public broadcasting is something Britain does well.  We should be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">proud of it and support it. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="39" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.68pt; padding-left:14.32pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">How should the BBC be governed, regulated and held accountable beyond 2016?</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="40" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.68pt; padding-left:14.32pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Here I support the CPBF in its view that the Board of Governors should be democratically elected and that there should be more devolution to democratically elected national bodies.    </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="41" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.68pt; padding-left:14.32pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">In a constantly evolving communications environment, does a 10-year Royal Charter and Agreement with the Secretary of State, together provide the most appropriate constitutional framework for the BBC?  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="42" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.68pt; padding-left:14.32pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">I am in two minds on this issue.  I support the CPBF’s informed and expert view.  Yet personally I have some sympathy for the Royal Charter solution, archaic though it is.  It seems to indicate that something is special, heritage, if you like; something that this country values greatly, if not always rationally.  So I remain undecided. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">December 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>